Building a Business Your Audience Can’t Help But Notice

If you have ever chosen to buy a pair of Nikes over the dusty, offbrand shoes sitting next to them, you know the value of a company creating familiarity with their brand. And if you’ve ever noticed a restaurant or business for the first time because of its “For Sale” sign, you also know the impact of obscurity.

It’s not enough to provide a quality product. People have to know about it, too.

Your decision to pick up the Nike shoes didn’t happen in a moment.

It happened because you saw the Nike poster on main street. You saw the 30-second ad on YouTube. You saw celebrities winning basketball games--wearing Nikes. You saw your friend wearing a pair at the gym.

Without you being aware, Nike has skilfully surrounded you with reminders of who they are. Everywhere you look, you see their iconic “swoosh.”

Because you see it everywhere you look, you may subconsciously feel like you are missing out on something great. 

It doesn’t matter that most people don’t even wear Nike. What matters is that everywhere you turn, you see them. From your mind’s perspective, “Everyone is doing it.”

**Why Branding Isn’t Just About a Pair of Shoes**

Now, let’s say your business offers top-notch service. It’s relevant, high-quality, and fairly-priced. But no one is noticing you. Your cold-calls, online ads, and requests for referrals bring in so few new customers you wonder how much longer your business can last.

The people who do walk in the door are surprised to hear how long you’ve been here\!

You need familiarity among your target audience. You know this. But how do you do that?

Familiarity depends on repeated encounters. This means positioning yourself in every place your target customer looks. You know your job is done when they walk away thinking (whether consciously or not): “Man, this guy is everywhere\! He must be running a big business--everyone seems to like him.”

Your customers are subconsciously asking “Who do I trust more? Who is more experienced, more professional--bigger?” They don’t answer it by fact. They answer it by their perception.

By targeting people on multiple platforms and media, you create familiarity with your target prospects, shaping their bias toward your company when they’re ready to buy.

**Here are a few tips to get you started:**

1. Target your audience with ads on various Social Media, choosing from Facebook, Google, YouTube, Twitter, and even Instagram.  
2. Sell or give away merchandise your customer can wear. Merchandise creates a sense of community among your customers “I am a part of something great\!” Plus, it’s “free” advertising. (So make it nice enough to wear\!)  
3. Put a magnet sign on your car. (One business owner did that to his own car, then heard people comment about his fleet that he had throughout the city\!)  
4. Provide interesting, non-promotional content your audience would find interesting or beneficial. This lets people become familiar with who you are before they ever step foot in your store.

As a small business owner, you don’t need the whole world familiar with your brand, just your target audience. Make yourself a common, likeable figure among their circles by targeting them on multiple online media, mailing them physical ads, collaborating with other companies they are familiar with, and possibly even showing up at live events they attend.

Once your business starts consistently showing up in their world, you can be sure they will start showing up in yours.
